Two or more propositions, united together by a particle, are called hypothe- tical; though more than one, their principal idea is one, and depends on the relation between each of the propositions and the particle. Their specific difference thus depends on the particle itself3 and as there are seven (and, or, if, because, more than, where, when) there are also seven sorts of hypothetical propositions: the copulative, the disjunctive, the conditional, the cazcsal, the comparative, the local, and the temporal.
